## git init

**Purpose**: Initialize a new Git repository in your project directory.

**When to use**: When you're starting a new project and want to enable version control.

### Example:
```bash
cd my-project
git init
```

**Output**:
```
Initialized empty Git repository in /path/to/my-project/.git/
```

**What it does**: Creates a hidden `.git` folder that stores all version history and metadata.

---

## git clone

**Purpose**: Create a local copy of a remote repository on your computer.

**When to use**: When you want to download an existing project from GitHub or another Git host.

### Example:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
```

**Output**:
```
Cloning into 'repository'...
remote: Enumerating objects: 42, done.
Receiving objects: 100% (42/42), done.
```

**What it does**: Downloads the entire repository history and creates a working directory with all files.

### Clone into a specific folder:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git my-folder
```

