## git push

**Purpose**: Upload your local commits to a remote repository (like GitHub).

**When to use**: When you're ready to share your work with others or back up your commits.

### Push to default branch:
```bash
git push
```

### Push to a specific branch:
```bash
git push origin main
```

### Push a new branch to remote:
```bash
git push -u origin feature-branch
```
*(The `-u` flag sets up tracking so future pushes don't need the branch name)*

### Push all branches:
```bash
git push --all
```

**Output**:
```
Enumerating objects: 5, done.
Counting objects: 100% (5/5), done.
Delta compression using up to 8 threads
Compressing objects: 100% (3/3), done.
Writing objects: 100% (3/3), 356 bytes, done.
To https://github.com/username/repository.git
   a1b2c3d..e4f5g6h  main -> main
```

**What it does**: Synchronizes your local commits with the remote repository so others can see your changes.

---

## git pull

**Purpose**: Download and integrate remote changes into your local repository.

**When to use**: When your teammates have pushed new commits and you want to update your local copy.

### Pull from default branch:
```bash
git pull
```

### Pull from a specific branch:
```bash
git pull origin main
```

**Output**:
```
remote: Enumerating objects: 3, done.
Unpacking objects: 100% (3/3), done.
From https://github.com/username/repository
   e4f5g6h..x7y8z9a  main       -> origin/main
Updating e4f5g6h..x7y8z9a
Fast-forward
 feature.js | 10 ++++++++++
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+)
```

**What it does**: 
1. Fetches remote changes
2. Merges them into your current branch
3. Updates your working directory

